INSERT INTO ftotm (ftotm_id, ftotm_tkid, ftotm_month, ftotm_year, ftotm_text, ftotm_show) VALUES
(1, 1332, 10, 2009, 'Tiffany has been a fan of Star Wars since she was a kid, watching the original trilogy on cable. Her inspiration for joining the 501st was originally to have a really cool Stormtrooper costume, but then discovered that the 501st Legion was a BUNCH of Stormtroopers and other Star Wars characters that liked to hang out, make money for charity, and have fun!\r\n\r\nTiffany\'s favorite event to date was the Whitecaps Star Wars Night in 2007, because she got to go onto the field a do a bunch of crazy stuff in armor. Tiffany says that \"being in the 501st makes me feel like I am giving back to the world by helping raise money for the less fortunate.\"\r\n\r\nOutside of the Legion, \"Cujo,\" as most of us know her, is a full time student who is working towards getting her EMT license and is a black belt in Tae Kwon Do. When asked about her nickname, she said \"it was a nickname given to me by my Tae Kwon Do instructors many years ago. It just sort of stuck.\" She is also an admitted Internet and gaming junkie who likes to play World Of Warcraft.', 1),
(2, 2125, 11, 2009, 'Robert Amid has been a fan of Star Wars since the first time he saw A New Hope (or Star Wars, as it was called back then)\r\nat a drive-in. That showing also happened to have some costumers at the concessions building there that night as well, planting the seed for what would come later. Rob\'s first run in with the 501st was at Motor City Comic Con, where he saw \"cool armor\" and was \"blown away.\"\r\n\r\nRob\'s favorite events so far as a member have been the West Michigan Whitecaps games. Rob says that joining the 501st has\r\nchanged his life in many ways such as developing a lot more skills from building armor, but more importantly \"all the cool people that I\'ve met and the good friends they\'ve become.\"\r\n\r\nOutside of the Legion, \"Freak Nasty Fester,\" as some of us have come to call him, is a Continuous Improvement Manager in the aerospace industry. When asked about his board name, he said \"Salt shaker + shaved head + being with Blizz in a bar = nickname.\" Outside of the 501st, Rob\'s favorite pastimes are collecting Star Wars stuff (specifically Fett stuff, clones, Master Replicas/efx and Gentle Giant) and he is also very active in his church as a high school youth leader and a member of the board of trustees.\r\n\r\nIn his personal life, Rob is married to Tracy who is also a 501st member (ID 3153) and is a father of 2. His other\r\naccomplishments include nominations to West Point and the Naval Academy (but did not go to either as he wanted to go to the Air Force ROTC), Society of Manufacturing Lean Certified, guest speaker for National SME event in Grand Rapids and is a three-time Graduate Assistant for Dale Carnegie.', 1),
(3, 2280, 12, 2009, 'Robert Brang has been a fan of Star Wars since the first time he saw Return Of The Jedi at a Drive in with his mom and dad. Rob\'s dad would buy him the toys and his favorite one that he was given was Luke Skywalker.\r\n\r\n\"Up until 2 yrs ago I thought it was a rare item, since I had not seen any like it. It was then that I found out my dad could not find Luke, and got me a Battlestar Galactica Starbuck toy, took it from the package and told me it was Luke.\"\r\n\r\nRob\'s first run in with the 501st was at the Make-A-Wish Benefit Comedy Show in Livonia. It was an event for Katie Johnson and Rob\'s son Dylan who was 4 at the time, was a big Star Wars fan. In his own words, \"I was telling him all day, that \'You better start being good, \'cause I know Darth Vader\'. He did not see Vader or the TKs there and when we pulled in to the parking lot, we made our way to the front door. When Vader walked out, Dylan turned bright red and clung to my hand. That was the day, that I decided I wanted to join.  For the next half a year, I would show up to events and get Dylan\'s pics taken with all the troops\".\r\n\r\nRob\'s favorite events so far as a member have been the 2007 Thanksgiving Day Parade and various Motor City Comic Cons. In his own words, \"Motor City is a fun time to hang out with friends and meet new ones from other Garrisons. It has gotten bigger with each year, and in 2010 I am running it for the 501st. I have big shoes to fill, as Jay Shimko and Dan Provost have done a great job over the past years.\" Rob says that joining the 501st has changed his life in many ways such as meeting \"a ton of people that I hope to be friends with for a long time, even after my 501st days\".\r\n\r\nOutside of the Legion, Rob is a manager for a medical supply warehouse and lives in Livonia with his fiancee Diana (who is also a member of the GLG) and their son, Dylan who also likes to troop. Rob\'s hobbies include playing paintball (which he used to play competitively), airsoft and a little bit of gaming thrown in for good measure. Rob\'s accomplishments outside the 501st include being an Eagle Scout, a rank which only about 2% of all boys who join the Boy Scouts attain, and placing in the top 3 nationally with his paintball team.', 1),
(4, 8987, 1, 2010, 'Amanda Raimondo has been a fan of Star Wars since the first time she saw The Empire Strikes Back on the big screen. Empire also happens to be her favorite of the movies and that was the main reason that she chose to do a Snowtrooper costume.\r\n\r\nAmanda\'s favorite event so far as a member was the 2009 West Michigan Whitecaps\' Star Wars Night- her first event. Amanda says that joining the 501st has changed her life because of \"the people that we met, it\'s feels as if our family has expanded\". Amanda says that her inspiration for joining the 501st was her love of Star Wars and also seeing the reaction the kids have when they are around the 501st in action.\r\n\r\nOutside of the Legion, \"Sno-e,\" as some of us have come to call her, is a retail manager (Set Execution Supervisor) for the last 22 years and counting. Amanda also put herself through art school with a double major in photography and illustration and was successful at one time with her artwork. Due to certain life changes her artwork has taken the backseat but \"I have been waiting for [her husband] \'Pesci\' to finish our new office so I can have an art studio again.\"\r\n\r\nIn her personal life, Amanda is married to Dave \"Pesci\" Raimondo (TB 8789) and loves to read and draw. \"Pesci has been begging me to start some illustrations of Star Wars. so I guess when I do start to draw again, It will probably be something from Hoth.\"', 1),
(5, 5750, 2, 2010, 'Martin Pondell has been a fan of Star Wars since the first time he saw it with his parents in the theater.\r\n\r\n\"I was just amazed by everything I was seeing so much so that I kept looking around to see where the ships were coming from.\"\r\n\r\nMarty\'s favorite event so far has been the Detroit St. Patrick\'s Parade, an event he does every year. He was inspired to join the group after being a member of the local Star Wars Fan Force group, R2 Detroit, and noticed some of his friends from that group were also members of the 501st. After doing some events with them and seeing all the wonderful things the 501st did, he was hooked and set off on \"one of the best adventures of my life.\"\r\n\r\nOutside of the Legion, \"Darktrooper013\" is a Loss Prevention and Safety Patrol Officer for McKinley,Inc. His board name is character from the Star Wars expanded universe. Marty says, \"I read a short story on Darktroopers and and was fascinated by them and the destruction that only one of these bad boys could cause. I decided on using the name.\r\n\r\n\"If you\'re going to use the name of on Imperial super battle droid, might as well use the most unlucky number, 13.\"\r\n\r\nFor fun, Marty enjoys bike riding on a quiet day or hitting the water on his wave-runner some place where there is more water and less people and also enjoys collecting Star Wars toys.\r\n\r\nIn his personal life, Marty recently returned and graduated from college with his associates degree in Criminal Justice. He also received highest honors for doing this. In his own words, \"no one was more surprised at this than me.\"', 1),
(6, 9807, 3, 2010, 'Aaron \"Foo\" Combs has been a fan of Star Wars \"since birth.\" It was the first movie his parents took him to. Aaron says,\"Han Solo being tortured really affected me, and not in the good way if you know what I mean. I have had an issue with things being near my eyes ever since. You know, the whole \'red hot sparking pokers in the face\' thing. Ouch. That was a disturbing walk down memory lane. Maybe that explains some of my violent tendencies.\"\r\n\r\nAaron\'s favorite event so far has been the Grand Rapids Griffins event in \'09. He was a huge hit as the first Republic Commando in Michigan.\r\n\r\n\"Now that our Delta Squad is growing, I can\'t wait to storm some suites to empty peoples wallets!\" he says.\r\n\r\nAaron loves the hockey events because \"you don\'t sweat that much!\"\r\n\r\nOutside of the Legion, \"Foo\" serves in the Army. He has been in the Military Police for 14 years and started out life in the Army enlisted.  Foo then went to the Dark Side and became an officer, achieving the rank of Captain. He currently teaches in the Reserve Officers Training Corps.\r\n\r\n\"I must have done something right if they trust me to create new Lieutenants.\"\r\n\r\nAaron has also walked away from three helicopter crashes and was in charge of the Guantanamo Bay detention facilities.  He has also perfected the Jedi mind trick for getting store employees to pull things out of the back room for him as well.\r\n\r\nWhen asked about his nickname, Foo explained \"F.O.O. is an acronym for \'Force Of One\'. I was at a Green Day concert back in college and some dude sucker-punched me. I wasn\'t real happy and he and his friends wanted to roll. So, fight ensued and I ending up taking 5 guys down. One of my instructors was there and saw it and said \'man you were a force of one out there.\' He later called me F.O.O. and it stuck.\"\r\n\r\nOutside the Legion, Aaron is happily married and the proud father of two daughters. He is very active in his church, where he sings in the praise team, does drama, and leads the high school youth group. He used to play video games or tried to read a Star Wars book in his free time, but now he is the official seamstress and resin caster for Republic Commando costumes around the world. He makes the RC neckseal for all RCs, and the Sniper Attachments for Sev and other sniper builds.', 1),
(7, 3822, 4, 2010, 'Shannon Trombley has been a fan of Star Wars since the first time she saw \"The Empire Strikes Back\" on the big screen and was hooked ever since.\r\n\r\n\"I was fascinated me the most was how did they get those AT-AT Walkers to walk in the movie. I even remember the dream I had after seeing \'The Empire Strikes Back.\' In the dream, I was trying to rescue Princess Leia but Darth Vader kept chasing me around her. Like Princess Leia needs to be rescued since she rescues either Luke, Han, or both though out the original trilogy.\"\r\n\r\nShannon\'s favorite event so far as a member of both the 501st and the Rebel Legion have been the AJ\'s Family Fun Park events. \"Where can one see Star Wars characters driving around in go-carts, bumper boats, hitting baseballs in a batting cages, and playing putt-putt golf? It\'s a fun event where the troopers can do more then walk around and have pictures taken of them by people.\"\r\n\r\nAbout being a 501st member, Shannon says \"I don’t think joining the 501st has changed my life so much but it has given me a second family. We have our ups and downs at times, but it seems we always come together for a charity event or for any event for that matter. The way we bring smiles to the fans faces is a great thing to see during events and it shows we are doing some good in this world.\"\r\n\r\nOutside of the Legion, \"Stiger1\", \"Bumpers\", \"West Side Hussy\", or \"Panther\" as some of us have come to call her is a postal clerk at the Richland Post Office. She sorts the mail to the right routes and waits on customers at the window. She has been with the Postal Service for a total of nine years and with the Richland Post Office for one year in June.\r\n\r\nIn her personal life, Shannon collects some Star Wars toys/collectibles (especially young Obi-Wan Kenobi). She likes to read Star Wars novels, of which she says \"I need to get back into [it] soon because I\'m behind in the \'Fate of the Jedi\' series.\"\r\n\r\nShannon likes to watch movies and some television, listen to music, and claims she is on Facebook way too much. Shannon also has received an Associate of Arts degree from Kellogg Community College and was a member of Phi Theta Kappa. She was on the National Dean’s List two years in a row.  Shannon has also received a Bachelor of Arts degree from Western Michigan University, and was a member of the Golden Key National Honor Society.', 1),
(8, 3411, 5, 2010, 'Jackie Wagensomer\'s earliest Star Wars memory takes her back to playing with the original toys when they first came out, she was as she said she was \"too young to go see the movie.\" Being the only girl in a neighborhood of 5 boys, she was always stuck playing with them and their action figures. By default, she was always Princess Leia.\r\n\r\nJackie enjoys every event for different reasons. \"Whether it’s the fun we have or the smiles and awe-struck looks from the kids, every event is worth every moment!\" Motor City Comic Con in 2009 was her first event in armor so \"that holds a special place in my heart.\"\r\n\r\nBeing a part of the 50st has changed her life in many ways. Jackie says that she\'s been blessed to make so many new and wonderful friends and loves the fact that her and her husband Tony (CC-7195)\'s garage (The Man Cave) is usually a flurry of activity with so many costumes being made. She also enjoys the downtime just visiting with friends. One of the biggest changes for her has been the smiles on so many children’s faces when they see one of the characters. \r\n\"To witness it is cool. To live it from inside the costume brings me so much joy!\"\r\n\r\nWhen asked abut her board name, Jackie says \"My husband created it for me. He’s Wags, I’m his better half, so it became \'mama_wags.\'\"\r\n\r\nOutside of the Legion, Jackie is a Senior Human Resource Specialist for a medical device and infection prevention manufacturer and is responsible for staffing, administration, and labor relations for two UAW-represented facilities. She loves to spend time with her kids and their various activities, loves to read and \"will lose myself in a book for an entire day if I can!\"\r\n\r\nShe also has a Bachelors Degree in Business Management, a Professional in Human Resources Certification, and is one class away from her Masters Degree in Human Resource Management. She\'s also the very proud mom to \"three wonderful kids – my best accomplishment yet!\"', 1),
(9, 1800, 6, 2010, 'Rome Ohnui has been a fan of Star Wars since his parents took him to see \"The Empire Strikes Back.\" He was scared for Han when he was in the carbon freezing chamber the first time watching it, so the second time, his father jokingly put his hands over his eyes during the scene. Rome pushed his hand away because he needed to watch.\r\n\r\nRome\'s favorite event so far has been the Rose Parade in Pasadena in 2007. Bringing together a United Nations of Star Wars fans to spend an entire week preparing for such a public spectacle was among the greatest privileges he could have ever been honored to receive.\r\n\r\n\"While marching in the parade itself was the pinnacle of our hard work, it was definitely the camaraderie shared at the hotel bar, lounge, and out and about in the immediate surroundings just outside Hollywood with 501st members from around the world that made the experience truly worthwhile.\"\r\n\r\nRome started off with a TIE Pilot costume and joined Omega Wing. He hadn\'t given much thought to trooping while a member of Omega Wing, but since Omega Wing was -- at the time -- the premier destination for all things TIE pilot, a lot of members of Omega Wing were also concurrent members of the 501st. That exposure eventually led him to discovering the 501st and he became a member in April of 2004.\r\n\r\n\"Looking back over the last 6 years, I\'ve realized that the 501st has completely changed my life\'s direction. The majority of my friends that I have now have been through 501st connections. And having served as the Legion Captain of the Guard for three years has taught me invaluable management skills -- both in terms of information and people -- that have been parlayed into my regular job.\"\r\n\r\nRome\'s nickname, \"Crimson\", started as a result of a music project he was involved in called Red Witch. Since he needed a user name when joining message boards and forums, he opted to use the analogous \"Crimson Warlock.\" Over time, typing all of that became tedious, so he just shortened it to \"Crimson\".\r\n\r\nWhen it comes to work, Rome is a computer tech for a public school district. He has fixed computers and readjusted people\'s thinking about computers professionally for 12 years. For the last two years, he\'s been responsible for the technology asset management for the district. In his own words, \"It\'s in this task that my management experience gained through the 501st have been handy\".\r\n\r\nOutside of the Legion, Rome likes to play bass guitar, dabble in bagpipes and build websites just for the fun of it. He recently redesigned and rebuilt the Web site of his local brewpub, along with a back-end database administration to run it all. Rome currently resides happily in Metro Detroit with his wife Lori and their dog Lucy.', 1),
(10, 3842, 8, 2010, 'Justin Overholt has been a lifelong fan of Star Wars. Some of his earliest memories of of watching Return of the Jedi and loving all of the different aliens in Jabba\'s palace. When he was 4 or 5, he was bitten by the Star Wars costuming bug and dressed up like an Ewok for Halloween.\r\n\r\nJustin first heard about the 501st while building his Boba Fett costume. There were many people on The Dented Helmet that were talking abut the 501t, so he decided to check out what they were all about. He soon discovered that it was a group of people, \" joined together to bring the magic of Star Wars to so many for such a great cause\".\r\n\r\nSince joining, Justin\'s favorite events have been the Weird Al concert and trooping with Jeremy Bulloch in Grand Rapids for Make-A-Wish. He also says, \"Birthdays and weddings are always a blast. Parades are fun. Any event that involves kids in any way is always so much fun. Seeing the look in their eyes as they see Darth Vader and all the characters is the best.\"\r\n\r\nJustin\'s boardname (biomechanoid56) comes from the painting style of his favorite artist, HR Giger. In college, his ceramic work was influenced by Giger\'s bio-mechanical style of painting. Justin spent a lot of time studying his style, paintings and sculptures. This was also around the time Justin joined the 501st and the name was born.\r\n\r\nOutside of the 501st, Justin is a husband and a stay at home dad with his 2 year old son. He does work every Sunday at the Toledo Museum of Art in their family center, working with kids making different art projects each week. He is also working to be a freelance artist as well. Right now, Justin\'s hobbies include art (drawing, painting, sculpting), gardening (mostly carnivorous plant and voodoo lilies), and exotic pets as well. He still has 4 tarantulas, 2 mossy frogs, 1 fire belly toad, 1 axolotl and a bearded dragon.\r\n\r\nJustin has a bachelors degree in ceramics and Psychology as well as an Associates degree in Graphic Design. Some of his paintings and sculpture have taken second award at a local at show. One of his biggest accomplishments is that his 2 year old can name most of the major characters from the Trilogy.', 1),
(11, 3829, 9, 2010, 'Chris Brown\'s earliest Star Wars memories consist of a few things. He remembers seeing the re-release of Star Wars at a Drive In theater in 1979 when he was almost 4. He also remembers chewing the heads off of his brother\'s action figures when I was younger. To this day, Chris\'s brother still threatens to bite off the heads of some of his rarer figures. When he was 5, his mom listed in his baby book that his favorite book was Star Wars and he had a Star Wars cake. It\'s pretty safe to say that he was a fan at a young age.\r\n\r\nBeing a member of the 501st and Rebel Legions has given Chris the chance to make friends, some who are more like his family at this point. It\'s also given him an outlet for his constant need to tinker and make things. Being an active member in 2 Legions has also given him the chance to help out other members and potential recruits as the Republic Commando Advisor on CT.net. He sometimes gets some oddball questions here and there, but, \"it\'s really cool to have a hand in shaping the direction that the RC\'s will go within the 501st\".\r\n\r\nBack in 2002, \"Jaster\" went to a costume party in a $60 Jango costume from Rubies, complete with homemade cardboard jetpack and modified Rubies deluxe helmet. He knew that there had to be something better out there for the next year and found The Dented Helmet. He started working on an accurate Jango right after Halloween that year and later on, in the Fall of 2003, met Jay Shimko at Gibraltar Trade Center during a toy show and he gave Chris a Midwest Garrison business card. From there, he completed his costume, was approved and became BH3829.\r\n\r\nWhen Chris first needed any sort of screen name, he would usually use Jaster Mereel. When he first starting using it on Prodigy, the name was actually supposed to be Boba Fett\'s true identity. Later on, he used it for my name on the Midwest Garrison\'s boards and eventually it was shortened to Jaster.\r\n\r\n\"I think it was Shimko who started calling me Jaster in person. We were at an armor party or some sort of outing and there were too many Chris\'s at the party. He yelled over, \"Hey Jaster\" and the board name became the nickname.\"\r\n\r\nJaster\'s favorite events so far have been the Port Huron Icehawks events. In his own words...\r\n\r\n(I liked the events) \"not really so much for the game, but for the charity we were supporting during those events. My father was diagnosed with Primary Progressive Multiple Sclerosis in 2000 and is currently receiving help from Council on Aging\'s Washington Life Center. Being able to help them out by participating in a 501st event was the easiest way I knew to return the favor\".\r\n\r\nOutside the 501st, Chris is an electrician working for a small company for the last 13 years in Shelby Township. His main specialty is troubleshooting and service work. He enjoys being around people and most of all fixing their electrical problems. Some of his other passions are cooking, playing the bass guitar, reading, karaoke and watching movies. Chris have been married to his wife Carolyn (SL 6156) for 15 years as of this October. He was a member of Mensa from 1991-1993, but let his membership go because \"it was boring\" and it looked good on college applications. On the Rebel Legion side of things, Jaster is also the GLG Liaison for the Great Lakes Base.', 1),
(12, 7759, 10, 2010, 'Michael Arnold has been a fan of Star Wars ever since he saw Lord Vader step into the blockade runner with that long black cape. The next two hours changed his life forever.As part of his love for Star Wars, he I always wanted a life size Darth Vader to put into a room in his house. One day he realized that he had a chance to actually dress as him.\r\n\r\nSince joining in May of 2008, Michael has enjoyed many events, but the A.J.\'s events have been his favorite. Seeing all the kids, parents and troopers riding the go-carts and playing games has made this annual event incredibly enjoyable to him. Being a part of the 501st has changed his life knowing that he is helping to raise money for charities and knowing it is going to people that need help. He also loves to see the kids faces when they see all of their favorite characters.\r\n\r\n\"Zod\", as some of us have come to know him, was given his nickname by a couple of friends growing up.\r\n\r\n\"That was a childhood nickname that David \"Pesci\" Raimondo (TB8789) and a good friend (that passed away a couple of years ago) used to call me after seeing Superman 2 with General Zod and the funny line- \'Kneel before Zod!\' So as a tribute to my friend, Pesci said we should use that and the rest is history.\"\r\n\r\nOutside of the 501st, Michael is an I.T. Manager for a property management company in East Lansing, MI who also has a degree in Graphic Arts. He enjoys working on his family and friend\'s PC\'s as well as collecting Star Wars stuff. He has 2 sons and a granddaughter.\r\n\"Family is so important and cannot spend enough time with them, so I am hoping to get my son Nathan who has been doing NCS into armor soon and having him join the 501st when he turns 18.\"', 1),
(13, 2275, 11, 2010, 'Carl Nelson’s earliest Star Wars memories are of his Star Wars toys (some of which he still has today) and of him battling Darth Vader one Christmas morning. Sure Carl was a child and Vader was an inflatable punching bag, but it did not diminish the battle between good and evil. Perhaps this is why Carl joined the Rebel Legion as a Jedi prior to joining the 501st legion. But it did not take Carl long to be seduced to the dark side. “After I joined the Rebel Legion and came to my first troop, I was impressed with the armored Imperial characters and the fact that you could not see their faces made it appear even more fun.”\r\n\r\nBeing a part of the 501st has changed Carl’s life for the better. He has learned to be more outgoing and has become friends with others that he otherwise would have never known if not for Star Wars. He also really enjoys seeing the benefit of the Legions Charity work. “Helping out a good cause just makes you feel great.” Carl knows the fans appreciate what we do too. Seeing those awe-struck faces and the next generation of fans enjoying something he loved as a child is wonderful.\r\n\r\nSince joining in May of 2006, he has enjoyed many events, but Star Wars in Concert at the Palace of Auburn Hills has been his favorite.\r\n\r\nHis board name “Noslen L\'Rac” was created by himself and is simply his name spelled backwards. His operating number is TR 2275 and his approved Legion costume is a Royal Guard.\r\n\r\nOutside of the Legion, Carl is a School Service Representative for Marshall Music Company in West Michigan. His hobbies include gardening, landscaping, home remodeling, music, church, politics, and anything his daughter is involved with. He is also pleased to be a graduate of Financial Peace University for which he is a coordinator and proud to be and grow as a Christian, father, and husband.', 1),
(14, 4702, 12, 2010, 'As a kid, Jesse\'s first theater experience was going to see a movie called Star Wars. It made a huge impression on him. Especially the scene where the star destroyer captures the blockade runner, and the Stormtroopers bust in with all that shiny white armor! Needless to say, he was hooked. Ever since then he thought it would be neat to have his very own TK digits.\r\n\r\nThat childhood dream finally happened in May of this year when Jesse was approved for membership with the 501st Legion as a Stormtrooper, and is now TK 4702 making him one of the newer members of the Great Lakes Garrison.\r\n\r\nJoining the 501st Legion has allowed Jesse to get more involved in the hands on building of Star Wars props and costumes in a way that he never imagined, and has since begun making his own custom made costume parts and accessories.\r\n\r\nWhen not in costume, Jesse is busy editing videos and producing motion graphics for a major chemical company in Midland, MI and has many years of experience in the creative/graphics industry. One of his recent videos won Best in Show at the 2010 Davey Awards, for Film/Video/TV.\r\n\r\nHis other hobbies include photography and music production. He is the lead song writer for an Industrial Music Group called Heavy Water Factory.\r\n\r\nHis proudest achievement is the birth of his new daughter. When asked about her, his reply: \"She rules!\"', 1),
(15, 501, 1, 2011, 'Well before the movies premiered in theaters, Doug\'s dad managed to get a comic book of Star Wars in 1976 and gave it to him for Christmas.  Being that he was only four years old and could barely read, he wasn\'t exactly able to follow the story.  He says, \"I thought the Empire was the good guys (they were the ones wearing white, after all), and Chewbacca was an evil monster.\"  It wasn\'t until he saw the movie half a year later that it all made sense.\r\n\r\nSpring forward to 1999 and Doug is reading comic book and comes across an ad for a convention called Star Wars Celebration.  He wanted to go, and why not since he had just purchased a Don Post TIE Pilot helmet and was looking for an excuse to make a complete TIE Pilot costume.  An event with thousands of people focused solely on Star Wars was certainly worth both the effort on the costume and the trip to Colorado.\r\n \r\nSo, with Black BDUs, medieval boots, gauntlets, homemade chest armor and chest box attached to the helmet with flexible metal hose, homemade patches, and a wrist communicator, he had his first Star Wars costume.  It all fit into his carry-on luggage and he was on my way to Colorado with his wife in tow.  \r\n\r\nUpon arrival at the convention, he donned the costume in public for the first time in the parking lot.  Doug says, \"Walking through that lot was so inspiring as kids and adults alike stared [open mouthed] and cried out in delight at the sight of me.\"  He posed for the first of many pictures for his new fans.  Such experiences were continuous over the next three days, and he was hooked on costuming.  But he was not member of the 501st, yet.\r\n \r\nIt was during the convention that he met up with members of the Swiss Garrison of the 501st Squad who showed up in force for Celebration.  It wasn\'t long before he had met nearly the entire 501st Squad – more than 20 Imperial costumers all together.  They explained to him how before an event they would coordinate amongst themselves trips to such events as conventions and always showed up in groups to achieve a spectacular presence.  He very much wanted to be a part of that.  \"Any time I was hanging out with at least a few of these 501st members, we\'d be ‘trapped\' for a half-hour or more while crowds of people took photographs and I loved every second of it,\" says Doug.  As soon as he got home, Doug sent in a picture of himself from the convention and became an approved member of the club, making him the first official member from the state of Michigan.  The club was growing rapidly following Celebration and already was totaling more than 30 members.  However, the closest members to him were a handful of troopers in Chicago and another small group in Toronto, so he did a lot of traveling those first few years to various events.  Within a few months the club had grown to more than a hundred members and the name was changed to the 501st Legion.\r\n \r\nWhile Doug has trooped many different events, Celebration II is probably his favorite event overall.  \"Any event that is entirely Star Wars themed is up at the top, and with 501st members acting as staff and security for the vastly overwhelmed convention organizers. We added a level of immersion in the Star Wars universe I had never seen before or since,\" says Doug.\r\n \r\nDoug is also recognized by his designation or Legion Member ID of TK-501, but just how did he obtain one of the coolest designations within the Legion?  \"Back when I joined, the preferred way of determining your member ID number was with your birthday.  So, when [501st Legion founder] Albin Johnson approved my membership photo, he gave me a call and asked what my ID number should be. I replied, ‘Well, as my birthday is on May 1st, I\'d like the designation 501.\'  He laughed and said ‘So you\'re the trooper who finally takes that one!\'”\r\n \r\nWhen not in costume, Doug is a computer programmer who designs data acquisition and process control software for engineering applications.\r\n \r\nDoug\'s hobbies outside of the 501st include live-action role play (LARP), steampunk costuming and his very own Star Wars online comic.  He is involved in multiple fantasy LARPs and a future LARP based on the Firefly series.  His love of costuming extends here where he has made a number of detailed costumes for the various characters he portrays.  He is working on a near-future mercenary LARP making use of Airsoft weapons.  Doug started a steampunk costume last year, and has been to one steampunk event so far.  He also draws a Star Wars online comic called Dewback Wing based on an online role play board he has been a part of since around the time he joined the 501st.  Check it out!  Shameless plug:  http://td501.comicgenesis.com/\r\n\r\nBeing a member of the Legion has affected Doug in many positive ways. He traveled a lot in those early years when the 501st Legion was in its infancy and it seemed like every event occurred in some other state.  He traveled to Chicago, Minneapolis, Pittsburg, Toronto, Montreal, Greensboro, Atlanta, Orlando, Columbus, and many other locations that he would otherwise not have seen.  Along the way, he met a lot of great people and made great friends at every event.  He has marched in numerous parades including Walt Disney World, spoken with numerous celebrities, and been on-stage with \"Weird Al” Yankovic.  \r\n\r\n\"My life wouldn\'t be nearly as rich and wonderful without the 501st”- Doug Fesko', 1),
(16, 9296, 2, 2011, 'Michael Karp has been a fan of Star Wars since the first time he saw “A New Hope” back in 1977. He joined the 501st Legion in November of 2006 after being inspired to build Boba Fett costume. “I wanted a 1:1 scale Boba Fett to wear and display”, says Michael. While in the process of building the Fett he learned about the 501st while attending a prop party. There he met a few members of what was then the Michigan Squad and they told him about the Legion and that is what pushed him to join. He never did finish the Boba Fett costume, but ended up joining the Legion as 501st Clonetrooper.\r\n\r\nSince joining the Legion in 2006, Michael has served as the Garrison Membership Liaison from 2008 through 2009 and as the Commanding Officer for the 2009 – 2010 term. He has trooped 49 events to date. When asked if he has a favorite his reply, “My first one.” favorite still is his first one. It was the Classic Toy and Collectibles Show in Grand Rapids in December of 2006. It was very exciting!” says Michael. “My time trooping, meeting other 501st and also meeting Jeremy “Boba Fett” Bulloch in person!” Being a member of the legion has changed his life by him allowing him to develop friendships with people all over the globe.\r\n\r\nOutside of the Legion, \"Ripcode,\" as some of us have come to call him, is a full time computer programmer and also a Paid-on-call Firefighter/Medical first responder.\r\nWhen asked about his board name, he said \"The Ripcode was a toy motorcycle made by Mattel. The line was called “Rrrumblers” which was produced in the early to mid 70’s. This particular model was only made in 1973. It is my favorite “Rrrumbler” still today\".\r\n\r\nOutside of the 501st, Michael is a husband and father. His favorite past times are hiking, kayaking, hunting and fishing. He and his wife Kelli, who is also a member of the 501st Legion, love to travel.', 1),
(17, 8306, 4, 2011, 'Matt\'s earliest Star Wars memory is the result of family movie night. His family would get together and watch sci-fi and action movies because his parents loved those genres. Out of all the movies we watched, Star Wars really stuck out from the rest because it held something magical and special for him.\r\n\r\n\"The characters were so unique and spectacular that you wished that you lived in that world\", says Matt. He was fascinated by light sabers and would dream that some how, some day he could have his own real working light saber and become a Jedi Knight.\r\nThat changed when his family bought The Empire Strikes Back. \"It changed my whole outlook on Star Wars\" says Matt. \"That\'s where we first meet Boba Fett and right then and there I fell to the Dark Side. I knew that some day I would have to build a Fett costume\".\r\n\r\nA few years later that came to fruition when he came across a Boba Fett costume on eBay. It needed some work but he had to have it. It wasn\'t until after he started modifying the costume that he heard about the 501st Legion and everything that they stand for. Matt says, \"I was really attracted to the fact that the 501st raises so much money for charity. I made it my goal over the course of the next year or so to make my Boba Fett 501st Legion approved so that I would be able to troop with fellow Star Wars enthusiasts, and share the joy of the Star Wars universe\".\r\n\r\nFor Matt, becoming a member of the 501st Legion has been a great experience. \"I have been able to meet new people who share my same passion for building movie accurate costumes and playing \"adult dress-up\". However, Matt feels the best part of being in the club is the looks on all the kids\' faces and how much they absolutely love seeing their heroes magically transported from the screen to real life.\r\n\r\nOne of Matt\'s favorite missions was the Build-A-Bear Star Wars release at Rivertown Mall in Grandville. \"The people in the mall were so surprised to see us in Star Wars costumes and it was rather enjoyable watching everyone\'s reactions, both children and adults alike\", says Matt.\r\nCould you imagine if you went to the mall when you were a child and there were characters from your favorite movie just hanging out? It would be better than seeing Santa and the Easter bunny put together.\r\n\r\nWhen Matt is not hunting down a smuggler for a bounty, one might be surprised to find out that he is a professional brewer for Founders Brewing Co. in Grand Rapids where he has worked since January 2007. \"I have always had a love for craft beer and enjoyed home brewing for many years in college. I was fortunate enough to know the right people who led me to the opportunity to work at Founders. It has been the best job I have ever had and cannot see myself ever leaving the beer industry. I love every aspect of my job even though at times it can be very physically and mentally demanding, but I take it one pint at a time\", says Matt.\r\n\r\nMatt creativity and love for build things does not stop at creating movie accurate costumes; he also loves to work with wood and has built his own Baroque stringed instrument called a Viola da Gamba (it\'s like a cello but with six strings and tied on frets) and plays Baroque music with the Early Music Ensemble at GVSU. Matt explains that Baroque stringed instruments have gut strings instead of metal, and are played very differently than their modern cousins. \"It takes quite a bit of discipline but in the end the sound is well worth it\". Matt also plays the Violone del Contrabasso which is the Baroque version of the modern String Bass. \"It has been a great experience sharing music with people performed on period instruments and using historically informed practices\", says Matt.', 1),
(18, 1148, 5, 2011, 'Brooke\'s first introduction to Star Wars was the result of what was once considered a rite of passage for most children; chickenpox.  \"I was in the sixth grade and was home sick with the chicken pox with nothing to do but try not to scratch and watch movies,\" says Brooke.  She had just about watched their entire movie collection when her mother found a recorded-from-TV copy of \"The Empire Strikes Back.\"  She let Brooke watch that and she loved it, but she wanted to see more and learn what happens, so her mom went out and rented the other two movies.  \"Yeah, I did see them out of order, but I was still hooked,\" says Brooke.\r\n\r\nShe has loved Star Wars ever since.  She made it to Celebration I and by the time Celebration II came around, she was already into Star Wars costuming.  Brooke says \"it was there that I was introduced to the 501st Legion and I instantly knew that I wanted to own armor and join up.\" \r\n\r\nBrooke has trooped over 60 events since joining the Legion in April of 2005.  When asked if she has a favorite, she says \"it would probably be the John Williams Tribute Concert in Toledo, OH. We were asked to help participate on stage. I and another trooper marched out on stage before Darth Vader came out. We stood on either side of the conductor. When Darth Vader came out, he force-choked the conductor and then started conducting the orchestra himself! When the conductor tried to come back, we troopers turned and focused our blasters at him. It was so much fun and the crowd really enjoyed it.\"\r\n\r\nBack in 2006, \"Thumper,\" as Brooke is known on the Garrison forum, got her nickname while at the Motor City Comic Con.  \"I had just gotten a new tattoo on my lower back of the imperial cog. I spent most of the after-party showing off my new ink. Roger (TD-0866) is the one who actually coined my nickname, by calling me Thumper that evening. And the name has stuck ever since,\" says Brooke.\r\n\r\nThe 501st Legion has changed her life for the better as she has met her fiancé Jason (TA-1703) and many wonderful lifelong friends through the 501st.\r\n\r\nOutside of the Legion, Brooke is a 3-D computer artist, specializing in computer generated imagery production, design, and visual communications.  She has a Bachelors of Fine Arts degree and her other interests include scrapbooking and photography, and cherishes time with her little rescued Sheltie, Abby.', 1),
(19, 130, 6, 2011, 'Jay Shimko heard about the 501st a long time ago. \"When I was doing research into making a Boba Fett statue for display I thought to myself, why not just make a display that I can wear? So, I was flipping through a Star Wars Insider and found a article on the 501st\". The year was 2002 and Jay soon found Andrew Miller (BH 542) online who already had a completed Boba Fett constume and he helped Jay along the way. That Boba Fett costume turned into a habit of costume building and collecting. Jay also built a Tusken Raider, Dengar, Tie Pilot, Rancor Keeper, Imperial Crewman, Snowtrooper and TK (Stormtrooper).\r\n\r\nJay has trooped over 50 events since joining the 501st in April of 2002, but perhaps his favortie event thus far has been Celebration 3. \"A few good friends packed up our vehicles and made the trek and had a experience of a lifetime. We got to meet many troopers from around the world, it was a good time!\", says Jay.\r\n\r\nHis earliest favorite Star Wars memories take him back to a time when his older brothers talked him into putting M-80\'s into his toy Millienum Falcon! \"They set the scene and we put figures in the ship and they had me all pumped up. It was great! The explosion was huge and the ship caught on fire. But the after effects were very traumatising...\"What do you mean, I cant play with my Millieunum falcon anymore?\", Jay remembers asking!\r\n\r\nHe and his best friend growing up played with Star Wars figures all the time. \"We would take hours to pick each figure and ship one by one, and then it would take hours to set up and we would really never have enough time in the day to actually play, but that was half the fun. I think that is why I am so into collecting the vintage action figures today.\"\r\n\r\nJay has met some of his best and closest friends in the 501st. \"When the Great Lakes Garrison was still the Michigan Squad, the troopers were a lot tighter than they are today, because there were so few of us. Most events were out of town and would require roadtrips. We made some tight bonds that way\", says Jay.\r\n\r\nWhen asked about the origin of his forum/board name, Jay explains it like this, \"It is a long explination and there are ancient mysteries about it....Im just kidding it is my last name.\"\r\n\r\nWhen he is not trooping, Jay makes a living running and operating a vacuum cleaner store and repair shop. \"It sucks.\" (See what I did there?), says Jay!\r\n\r\nHis other hobbies include: airsoft, costume and prop building, video games, poker, and he is a Freelance Illustrator and Vintage Star Wars collection NUT! \"I have every vintage loose and complete Star Wars figure from all three movies. My sickness is making me get into the Droids and Ewoks cartoon line of figures now\", says Jay.\r\n\r\nSome of Jay\'s accomplishments in life include: Becoming an official Lucasfilms artist, bridging the gap with Motorcity Comic Con and the 501st Legion as the event coordinator for many years, becoming the 501st\'s Trooper of the Month for April of 2007, Beating Lymphomia Cancer. His biggest accomplishment is my Baby Boy son (Matthew Allen) born in June of 2011.', 1),
(20, 1440, 7, 2011, 'Rich Clarke (TK 1440) was inspired to join the 501st Legion back in 1998 while attending the Motor City Comic Con at the old Novi Center. \"I saw real live Stormtroopers for the first time and they were having such a good time. I said to myself that looks like fun and a few years later I became a member of the 501st \".\r\n\r\nWhen asked what has been his favorite event since joining the Legion, his reply is, \"Well, it is kind of hard to nail down just one event but I would say Star Wars in Concert at the Palace of Auburn Hills has to be my favorite.\"\r\n\r\nRich is widely known by his nick name \"Tall TK\". One look at Rich in his Stormtrooper, or TK armor as we in the Legion call it, and you will see why everyone calls him \"Tall TK\". We all know the famous line from Star Wars when Princess Leia asks Luke, \"Aren’t you a little \"short\" to be a Stormtrooper\". Well, Rich is quite the opposite in his armor. He towers over most troopers and has been known to look Darth Vader in the eyes. \"How I got my nick name was a happy accident\" say Rich. \"I was in my Stormtrooper costume for the first time before I even joined the Legion at Motor City Comic Con in 2007, Jon \"Blasty\" Leopold ask me to sign a signup sheet and it said Tall TK with a question mark by it because they did not know who I was, and that is how I got my nick name.\"\r\n\r\nWhen not imposing the will of the galactic empire, Rich enjoys spending time as part of the Anime club of Michigan located in Royal Oak and as a camera man for the City of Royal Oak covering civic events.\r\n\r\nSince joining the 501st Legion in August of 2006 he has completed 24 events. He has also crossed paths with Star Wars celebrities the like of Jeremy Bullock (Original Boba Fett), Peter Mayhew (Chewbacca), and Julian Glover (General Veers).', 1),
(21, 5156, 8, 2011, 'Mike Lica (TK 5156) was inspired to join the 501st Legion while attending the Motor City Comic Con. “I saw a bunch of Star Wars characters walking around and I always admired the design of Stormtrooper armor, but I never thought there was a great organization like the 501st legion until that day”, says Mike.\r\nSoon after, Mike built his own Stormtrooper armor and joined the club. Since then he has trooped almost 50 events! When asked what has been his favorite event, he says “It would be difficult to say what my most favorite event is without first mentioning the most meaningful events like the hospital visits and fundraisers”. Mike has trooped in a lot of really fun events such as being on stage with Sugarland or Weird Al Yankovic in front of thousands of their fans but he says those type of events never compare to the one smile you can create by visiting a sick child in a hospital bed.”\r\n\r\nMike’s earliest Star Wars memory takes him back to when he was a kid. His mom worked at a local drug store. “Back then, they used to put trading cards in loaves of Wonder Bread. One day my mom brought home the entire set. The movie wasn\'t even released yet and while looking at the cards I saw a Stormtrooper for the first time!” He remembers it like it was yesterday. Shortly after seeing the movie, Mike’s dad came home with a bunch of Star Wars figures that he had purchased at Kmart. “I remember we opened them and stood them up on the table while tossing the packaging into the garbage. Who knew that they would be worth hundreds of dollars in the box? Nobody knew the impact that Star Wars would have on the world”. As a hobby Mike still collects Star Wars memorabilia and has a pretty extensive collection. His collection has expanded to building what he cannot buy – as Mike and his brother Jerry are building their very own R2D2 droid.\r\n\r\nSince joining the 501st Legion, Mike’s life has been very busy. “In one short year, I visited schools, hospitals, concerts, fundraisers, and hockey games just to name a few. Mike says, “All of the time I spent laying around doing nothing is gone. All of that wasted time now has a meaningful purpose.”\r\n\r\nWhen Mike is not imposing the will of the galactic empire, he operates a carpet cleaning, repair, and inspection service company. Before that, he served our country for 10 years in the Navy’s Submarine Force. He and his wife Kristie have raised two kids, Nic and Heather, who are both currently in college. He enjoys spending time with his wife and friends.', 1);
